how and why conversion has occurred. Contributors draw on various insights from social movement theory to religious studies to help outline its impact on national attitudes and activities, gender relations, identity politics, and reverse waves of missions from Latin America aimed at the American immigrant community. Unlike other studies on religious conversion, this volume pays close attention to who converts, under what circumstances, the meaning of conversion to the individual, and how the change affects converts’ beliefs and actions. The thematic focus makes this volume important to students and scholars in both religious studies and Latin American studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aConversion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBirman, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarozzi, Marí A Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChesnut, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleary, Edward L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleary, Edward L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCorr, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrigerio, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrard-Burnett, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGooren, Henri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovic, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmilde, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteigenga, Timothy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteigenga, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabula